# IPL Analytics & Match Prediction

A full end-to-end data science project analyzing IPL cricket data from Cricsheet (2008–2026), covering impact player rule analysis, player/venue statistics, and match outcome prediction.

---

## Project Structure

```
ipl-ml-project/
├── data/
│   ├── ipl_json/          # Raw Cricsheet JSON files (1243 matches)
│   └── processed/         # Cleaned CSVs generated by notebooks
│       ├── matches.csv        # 1243 matches, 64 feature columns
│       ├── deliveries.csv     # 295,732 ball-by-ball deliveries
│       ├── home_away_stats.csv
│       ├── best_venues.csv
│       ├── toss_by_venue.csv
│       ├── top_openers.csv
│       ├── top_pp_bowlers.csv
│       └── top_death_bowlers.csv
├── notebooks/
│   ├── 01_data_extraction.ipynb       # Raw JSON → CSVs
│   ├── 02_feature_engineering.ipynb   # Phase runs, boundaries, dot%
│   ├── 03_impact_player_analysis.ipynb # Impact player rule analysis
│   ├── 04_additional_analysis.ipynb   # Venue, team, player EDA + model features
│   └── 05_modeling.ipynb              # 4 ML models, evaluation, export
├── models/
│   ├── best_models.pkl        # Trained sklearn models
│   └── model_summary.json     # Performance summary
├── website/
│   ├── index.html             # Impact player analysis
│   ├── stats.html             # Player & venue stats
│   ├── model.html             # Live match predictor
│   ├── style.css              # Shared dark-theme styling
│   ├── script.js              # Impact player charts
│   ├── stats.js               # Stats page charts
│   ├── model.js               # Predictor logic
│   ├── data.json              # Impact player analysis data
│   ├── stats_data.json        # Stats page data
│   └── model_data.json        # Model coefficients + predictor data
├── requirements.txt
└── README.md
```

---

## 🔍 What This Project Does

### 1. Data Extraction (`01`)

Parses 1243 IPL match JSON files from Cricsheet into two clean tables:

- **matches.csv** — one row per match with toss, venue, result, teams
- **deliveries.csv** — one row per ball with batter, bowler, runs, wickets

### 2. Feature Engineering (`02`)

Builds match-level features from ball-by-ball data:

- Phase-wise runs (powerplay, middle, death overs)
- Boundary %, dot ball %, run rate per innings
- Team name normalization (Daredevils → Capitals, Kings XI → Punjab Kings, etc.)
- Venue consolidation (renamed stadiums, inconsistent naming)

### 3. Impact Player Analysis (`03`)

Tests the hypothesis: _did the Impact Player rule (introduced 2023) cause IPL scores to rise by encouraging more aggressive batting?_

**Key findings:**

- Average first innings score rose from **162 → 189 runs** (+26) after the rule
- 200+ scores went from **10% → 41%** of matches
- **Powerplay and middle overs drove the rise** — death overs stayed flat, contradicting the common assumption that Impact Player mainly helps death-over hitting
- **Openers' strike rate jumped from 125 → 150** (+24 points) — the biggest gainers by batting position
- **Boundary % rose, dot ball % fell, wickets barely changed** — batters scoring more freely without being dismissed more often
- Sixes per match rose from **11.2 → 17.6**
- Captains choosing to field rose from **63% → 77%**
- All 9 home grounds with sufficient data show a runs increase, from +10 (Chennai/Chepauk) to +38 (Hyderabad)
- **Bowling economy rose across all phases**, sharpest in powerplay (+1.70 runs/over)
- Both spin and pace got more expensive; neither lost wicket-taking ability

### 4. Additional Analysis (`04`)

- **Home vs away win %** per team — CSK has the strongest genuine home advantage (+14.9%)
- **Best venue per team** — not always their home ground
- **Toss advantage by venue** — Rajiv Gandhi Stadium shows lowest toss win rate (37.5%)
- **Top openers in Impact Player era** — Vaibhav Suryavanshi leads at 217.4 SR
- **Best powerplay bowlers** — Bumrah leads with 7.39 economy
- **Best death over bowlers** — Bumrah again at 7.15, Pathirana best wicket-taker (8.9 balls/wicket)
- **Model features engineered**: team form (rolling 5), H2H win rate, venue avg score, toss advantage by venue, home flag, season win rate, opposition bowling strength, batting SR vs spin/pace, H2H at specific venue

### 5. Modeling (`05`)

Four models trained on 2008–2022, tested on 2023–2026:

| Model               | Type                | Pre-match      | Post-Powerplay     |
| ------------------- | ------------------- | -------------- | ------------------ |
| Match winner        | Logistic Regression | 46.5% accuracy | **58.7% accuracy** |
| First innings score | Linear Regression   | MAE ±30.6 runs | MAE ±22.6 runs     |

**Key modeling findings:**

- Powerplay wickets lost > powerplay runs for predicting match winners
- Home advantage + H2H record are the two strongest pre-match signals
- Pre-match features cannot predict T20 scores (negative R²) — T20 variance is too high
- Knowing the powerplay score improves winner prediction by ~12 percentage points
- Simpler models (LR) outperformed Random Forest and XGBoost on this dataset size
- T20 cricket's inherent randomness limits pre-match predictability — honest ceiling ~60%

---

## 🌐 Website

Three-page interactive website built with vanilla HTML/CSS/JS and Chart.js:

- **Impact Player Analysis** (`index.html`) — 11 charts covering scoring trends, phase breakdown, role analysis, team adaptation, bowling impact
- **Player & Venue Stats** (`stats.html`) — top openers, powerplay/death bowlers, home vs away win %, toss advantage by venue
- **Match Predictor** (`model.html`) — live predictor using exported model coefficients, works entirely client-side with no server required

---

## Getting Started

### Prerequisites

- Python 3.9+
- Node/npm not required — website is plain HTML/CSS/JS

### Installation

```bash
git clone https://github.com/YOUR_USERNAME/ipl-ml-project.git
cd ipl-ml-project

python3 -m venv venv
source venv/bin/activate

pip install -r requirements.txt
```

### Data

Download the IPL JSON dataset from [cricsheet.org](https://cricsheet.org/matches/) and place the unzipped files in `data/ipl_json/`.

### Running the notebooks

Open each notebook in order in VS Code with the Jupyter extension. Start every session by running the master setup cell at the top of each notebook.

```bash
# each notebook has a master setup cell — run it first
# it rebuilds matches_df and deliveries_df from scratch
```

### Viewing the website

```bash
cd website
python3 -m http.server 8000
# open http://localhost:8000
```

